{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"A Blog","author":"Scott Williams"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"89171ffe-2117-5f8f-a356-3deb627c2e95","excerpt":"","html":"<div><div><div><div><div>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.randsinrepose.com/archives/2009/11/02/the_foamy_rules_for_rabid_tools.html\">Quoth the Rands</a>:</p>\n<p></p>\n<div>\n<span><span> </span>\n</span><blockquote class=\"gmail_quote\" style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0.8ex; border-left-width: 1px; border-left-color: #cccccc; border-left-style: solid; padding-left: 1ex;\">\n<span>My tools only do what I've told them to do. Back when </span><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dreamweaver\" title=\"Adobe Dreamweaver - Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia\" target=\"_blank\"><span><span><span>Dreamweaver</span></span></span></a><span> first landed, I wanted to love it. I was so tired of the repetitive motion of developing HTML pages and the idea of a tool that was going to visually handle that laborious process was appealing. Problem was, Dreamweaver changed my code... without asking. </span>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"gmail_quote\" style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0.8ex; border-left-width: 1px; border-left-color: #cccccc; border-left-style: solid; padding-left: 1ex;\"><span><br></span></blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"gmail_quote\" style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0.8ex; border-left-width: 1px; border-left-color: #cccccc; border-left-style: solid; padding-left: 1ex;\"><span>It what?</span></blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"gmail_quote\" style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0.8ex; border-left-width: 1px; border-left-color: #cccccc; border-left-style: solid; padding-left: 1ex;\"><span><br></span></blockquote>\n<blockquote class=\"gmail_quote\" style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0.8ex; border-left-width: 1px; border-left-color: #cccccc; border-left-style: solid; padding-left: 1ex;\"><span>Dreamweaver was attempting to be helpful, but the moment it reformatted my code, I threw a fit. YOU TOUCHED MY CODE. Dreamweaver never recovered from that horrendous first impression.</span></blockquote>\n<p></p>\n<div>I agree wholeheartedly.  </div>\n</div>\n</div></div></div></div></div>","frontmatter":{"title":"On Dreamweaver (and other 'magic' HTML editors)","date":"November 03, 2009"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/2009/11/03/on-dreamweaver-and-other-magic-html-editors/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/2009/10/31/if-i-were-a-competitor-to-atandt-and-the-ipho/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"If I were a competitor to AT&T (and the iPhone)"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/2009/11/04/magic-numbers-1/index.html/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Magic Numbers"}}}}